1 (9) A person's refusal to submit to a chemical test as
2 provided in subsection (6) is admissible in a criminal prosecution
3 for a crime described in section 625c(1) only to show that a test
4 was offered to the defendant, but not as evidence in determining
5 the defendant's innocence or guilt. The jury must be instructed
6 accordingly.
7 (10) As used in this section:
8 (a) "Controlled substance" means that term as defined in
9 section 7104 of the public health code, 1978 PA 368, MCL 333.7104.
10 (b) "Intoxicating substance" means that term as defined in
11 section 625.
12 Sec. 625c. (1) A person who operates a vehicle upon a public
13 highway or other place open to the general public or generally
14 accessible to motor vehicles, including an area designated for the
15 parking of vehicles, within this state is considered to have given
16 consent to chemical tests of his or her the person's blood, breath,
17 or urine, or other bodily fluid for the purpose of determining the
18 amount of alcohol or presence of a controlled substance or other
19 intoxicating substance, or any combination of them, in his or her
20 the person's blood, or urine, or other bodily fluid or the amount
21 of alcohol in his or her the person's breath in all of the
22 following circumstances:
23 (a) If the person is arrested for a violation of section
24 625(1), (3), (4), (5), (6), (7), or (8), section 625a(5), or
25 section 625m or a local ordinance substantially corresponding to
26 section 625(1), (3), (6), or (8), section 625a(5), or section 625m.
27 (b) If the person is arrested for a violation of section 601d,
28 section 626(3) or (4), or manslaughter, or murder resulting from
29 the operation of a motor vehicle, and the peace officer had
SCS H02293'25 (H-2) 031ced

11
1 reasonable grounds to believe the person was operating the vehicle
2 in violation of section 625.
3 (2) A person who is afflicted with hemophilia, diabetes, or a
4 condition requiring the use of an anticoagulant under the direction
5 of a physician is not considered to have given consent to the
6 withdrawal of blood.
7 (3) The tests shall must be administered as provided in
8 section 625a(6).
9 (4) As used in this section:
10 (a) "Controlled substance" means that term as defined in
11 section 7104 of the public health code, 1978 PA 368, MCL 333.7104.
12 (b) "Intoxicating substance" means that term as defined in
13 section 625.
14 Sec. 625g. (1) If a person refuses a chemical test offered
15 under section 625a(6), the peace officer who requested the person
16 to submit to the chemical test shall comply with subdivisions (a)
17 and (b). If a person submits to the chemical test or a chemical
18 test is performed under a court order and the test reveals an
19 unlawful alcohol content, or the presence of a controlled substance
20 or other intoxicating substance, or any combination of them, the
21 peace officer who requested the person to submit to the test shall
22 do all of the following, other than subdivision (b)(i):
23 (a) On behalf of the secretary of state, immediately
24 confiscate the person's license or permit to operate a motor
25 vehicle and, if the person is otherwise eligible for a license or
26 permit, issue a temporary license or permit to the person. The
27 temporary license or permit must be on a form provided by the
28 secretary of state.
29 (b) Except as provided in subsection (2), immediately do all
SCS H02293'25 (H-2) 031ced

12
1 of the following:
2 (i) Forward a copy of the written report of the person's
3 refusal to submit to a chemical test required under section 625d to
4 the secretary of state.
5 (ii) Notify the secretary of state by means of the law
6 enforcement information network that a temporary license or permit
7 was issued to the person.
8 (iii) Destroy the person's driver license or permit.
9 (2) If a person submits to a chemical test offered under
10 section 625a(6) that requires an analysis of blood, or urine, or
11 other bodily fluid and a report of the results of that chemical
12 test is not immediately available, the peace officer who requested
13 the person to submit to the test shall comply with subsection
14 (1)(a) and (b)(ii) and indicate in the notice under subsection
15 (1)(b)(ii) that a subsequent chemical test is pending. If the report
16 reveals an unlawful alcohol content, or the presence of a
17 controlled substance or other intoxicating substance, or any
18 combination of them, the peace officer who requested the person to
19 submit to the test shall immediately comply with subsection
20 (1)(b)(iii). If the report does not reveal an unlawful alcohol
21 content, or the presence of a controlled substance or other
22 intoxicating substance, or any combination of them, the peace
23 officer who requested the person to submit to the test shall
24 immediately notify the person of the test results and immediately
25 return the person's license or permit by first-class mail to the
26 address provided at the time of arrest.
27 (3) A temporary license or permit issued under this section is
28 valid for 1 of the following time periods:
29 (a) If the case is not prosecuted, for the earlier of 90 days
SCS H02293'25 (H-2) 031ced

13
1 after issuance or until the person's license or permit is suspended
2 under section 625f. The prosecuting attorney shall notify the
3 secretary of state if a case referred to the prosecuting attorney
4 is not prosecuted. The arresting law enforcement agency shall
5 notify the secretary of state if a case is not referred to the
6 prosecuting attorney for prosecution.
7 (b) If the case is prosecuted, until the criminal charges
8 against the person are dismissed, the person is acquitted of those
9 charges, or the person's license or permit is suspended,
10 restricted, or revoked.
11 (4) As used in this section:
12 (a) "Controlled substance" means that term as defined in
13 section 7104 of the public health code, 1978 PA 368, MCL 333.7104.
14 (b) "Intoxicating substance" means that term as defined in
15 section 625.
16 (c) "Unlawful alcohol content" means any of the following, as
17 applicable:
18 (i) If the person tested is less than 21 years of age, 0.02
19 grams or more of alcohol per 100 milliliters of blood, per 210
20 liters of breath, or per 67 milliliters of urine.
21 (ii) If the person tested was operating a commercial motor
22 vehicle within this state, 0.04 grams or more of alcohol per 100
23 milliliters of blood, per 210 liters of breath, or per 67
24 milliliters of urine.
25 (iii) If the person tested is not a person described in
26 subparagraph (i) or (ii), 0.08 grams or more of alcohol per 100
27 milliliters of blood, per 210 liters of breath, or per 67
28 milliliters of urine or, beginning 5 years after the state
29 treasurer publishes a certification under section 625(28), 0.10
